\section{Equating methods for multiple anchors}
\label{sec:appendMulti}
The assumptions presented above for the Tucker, nominal weights, and frequency estimation methods are extended here to the total score distributions $X_P$ and $Y_Q$ and two or more anchor tests $V_1, V_2, \dots, V_m$.

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Tucker
% Need to specify multi-anchor version of equations 34 through 37, in terms of matrices.

\subsection{Tucker}
\label{sec:appendTucker}
Tucker equating with multiple anchor tests involves a linear regression of total scores $X$ or $Y$ on a matrix of anchor scores $\BV$. For population $P$ taking $X$, the regression model can be expressed in matrix notation as
\begin{equation}
  \Bx_P = \delta_{X} + \BV_P\Bgamma_{X} + \Be_{X_P}, \label{eqn:reg1}
\end{equation}
where $\Bx_P$ is an $n \times 1$ column vector of total scores on $X$ for $n$ individuals, the scalar $\delta_{X}$ is the intercept, $\BV_P$ is an $n \times m$ matrix containing scores across $m$ anchor tests, $\Bgamma_{X}$ is an $m \times 1$ column vector of regression slopes, and $\Be_{X_P}$ is the $n \times 1$ column vector of residuals. Equation~\eqref{eqn:reg1} is used here to derive the unobserved components of Equations~\eqref{eqn:synthmx2} and \eqref{eqn:synthvx2} as functions of $\Bgamma_X$ and the observed means and standard deviations on $X$ and $\BV$. Similar procedures are used to derive the unobserved values for $Y$ in $P$.

Note that in Equation~\eqref{eqn:reg1} there are no population subscripts on the regression coefficients $\delta_{X}$ and $\Bgamma_{X}$. The Tucker method assumes that these coefficients are the same in $P$ as in $Q$. As a result, the total score means for $X$ can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
  \mu_{X_P} = \delta_{X} + \Bmu_{V_P}^{\prime}\Bgamma_{X} \label{eqn:mxp}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
  \mu_{X_Q} = \delta_{X} + \Bmu_{V_Q}^{\prime}\Bgamma_{X}, \label{eqn:mxq1}
\end{equation}
where the means of $\Be_{X_P}$ and $\Be_{X_Q}$ are 0. The unobserved mean on $X$ for $Q$ can then be obtained through substitution and some rearranging as
\begin{align}
  \mu_{X_Q} &= \delta_{X} + \Bmu_{V_Q}^{\prime}\Bgamma_{X} \nonumber \\
  &= \mu_{X_P} - \Bmu_{V_P}^{\prime}\Bgamma_{X} + \Bmu_{V_Q}^{\prime}\Bgamma_{X} \nonumber \\
  &= \mu_{X_P} + (\Bmu_{V_Q}^{\prime} - \Bmu_{V_P}^{\prime})\Bgamma_{X}. \label{eqn:mxq2}
\end{align}
The unobserved mean on $Y$ for $P$ is obtained through a similar process as
\begin{equation}
\mu_{Y_P} = \mu_{Y_Q} + (\Bmu_{V_P}^{\prime} - \Bmu_{V_Q}^{\prime})\Bgamma_{Y}. \label{eqn:myp}
\end{equation}
These values can then be used in Equations~\eqref{eqn:synthmx1} and \eqref{eqn:synthmy1} to estimate $\mu_{X}$ and $\mu_{Y}$.

Next, it is assumed that the residual variance for each regression model is equal across populations. With $\sigma_{E_X}^2$ representing the residual variance for both $P$ and $Q$, assuming these variances are equal, the total score variances on $X$ can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{X_P}^2 = \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}\BSigma_{V_P}\Bgamma_{X} + \sigma_{E_X}^2 \label{eqn:vxp}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{X_Q}^2 = \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}\BSigma_{V_Q}\Bgamma_{X} + \sigma_{E_X}^2, \label{eqn:vxq1}
\end{equation}
where $\BSigma_{V_P}$ and $\BSigma_{V_Q}$ are the $m \times m$ variance-covariance matrices for the anchor tests, and $\Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}$ is the row vector of $m$ anchor test slopes. The unobserved variance on $X$ for $Q$ can then be obtained through substitution and some rearranging as
\begin{align}
  \sigma_{X_Q}^2 &= \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}\BSigma_{V_Q}\Bgamma_{X} + \sigma_{E_X}^2 \label{eqn:vxq2} \nonumber \\
  &= \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}\BSigma_{V_Q}\Bgamma_{X} + \sigma_{X_P}^2 - \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}\BSigma_{V_P}\Bgamma_{X} \\
  &= \sigma_{X_P}^2 + \Bgamma_{X}^{\prime}(\BSigma_{V_Q} - \BSigma_{V_P})\Bgamma_{X}. \nonumber
\end{align}
The unobserved variance on $Y$ for $P$ can be obtained similarly as
\begin{equation}
  \sigma_{Y_P}^2 = \sigma_{Y_Q}^2 + \Bgamma_{Y}^{\prime}(\BSigma_{V_P} - \BSigma_{V_Q})\Bgamma_{Y}. \label{eqn:vyp}
\end{equation}
Equations~\eqref{eqn:vxq2} and \eqref{eqn:vyp} can then be used within Equations~\eqref{eqn:synthvx2} and \eqref{eqn:synthvy2} to obtain $\sigma_{X}^2$ and $\sigma_{Y}^2$. These derivations for the Tucker method are simple extensions of equations presented for a single anchor \citep[e.g.,][]{kolen2014test}. Tucker equating with multiple anchors was first discussed by \cite{gulliksen1950theory}.

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Nominal weights

\subsection{Nominal weights}
\label{sec:appendNominal}
Nominal weights mean equating with a single anchor \citep{babcock2012nominal} can also be extended to accommodate multiple anchor tests. Test $X$ is presented as an example. The column vector of total scores $\Bx_P$ is first expressed as
\begin{equation}
  \Bx_P = \begin{bmatrix}
  \mu_{x_P1}K_X \\
  \mu_{x_P2}K_X \\
  \vdots \\
  \mu_{x_Pn}K_X
  \end{bmatrix}
  =
  \Bmu_{x_{P}}K_X, \label{eqn:meanpropx}
\end{equation}
where $x_P$ represents an item response on $X$, $\mu_{x_P}$ is a mean item score or proportion correct taken across all items for an individual, and $\Bmu_{x_P}$ is a column vector of mean proportion correct for $n$ individuals. Total scores on the anchor tests are expressed similarly as
\begin{align}
  \BV_P &= \begin{bmatrix}
  \mu_{v_P11}K_{V_1} & \mu_{v_P12}K_{V_2} & \cdots & \mu_{v_P1m}K_{V_m} \\
  \mu_{v_P21}K_{V_1} & \mu_{v_P22}K_{V_2} & \cdots & \mu_{v_P2m}K_{V_m} \\
  \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
  \mu_{x_Pn1}K_{V_1} & \mu_{v_Pn2}K_{V_2} & \cdots & \mu_{v_Pnm}K_{V_m}
  \end{bmatrix} \nonumber \\
  &= \begin{bmatrix}
  \mu_{v_P11} & \mu_{v_P12} & \cdots & \mu_{v_P1m} \\
  \mu_{v_P21} & \mu_{v_P22} & \cdots & \mu_{v_P2m} \\
  \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
  \mu_{x_Pn1} & \mu_{v_Pn2} & \cdots & \mu_{v_Pnm}
  \end{bmatrix}
  \begin{bmatrix}
  K_{V_1} & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\
  0 & K_{V_2} & \cdots & 0 \\
  \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
  0 & 0 & \cdots & K_{V_m}  
  \end{bmatrix} \nonumber \\
  &= \Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V, \label{eqn:meanpropv}
\end{align}
where $v_P$ represents an item response on $V$, $\Bmu_{v_P}$ is an $n \times m$ matrix of mean proportion corrects for $n$ individuals on $m$ anchor tests, and $\BK_V$ is a diagonal matrix containing the numbers of items on each anchor test.

Next, the mean proportion correct versions of $\Bx_P$ and $\BV_P$ in Equations~\eqref{eqn:meanpropx} and \eqref{eqn:meanpropv} are used to obtain the regression slopes in Equation~\eqref{eqn:reg1}. With $\Bx_P$ and $\BV_P$ expressed in deviation scores, solving Equation~\eqref{eqn:reg1} for $\Bgamma_X$ results in the following familiar equation:
\begin{equation}
  \Bgamma_X = (\BV_P^{\prime}\BV_P)^{-1}\BV_P^{\prime}\Bx_P. \label{eqn:reg2}
\end{equation}
Substituting Equations~\eqref{eqn:meanpropx} and \eqref{eqn:meanpropv} into \eqref{eqn:reg2} then results in
\begin{equation}
  \Bgamma_X = (\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V)^{-1}\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{x_P}K_X. \label{eqn:reg3}
\end{equation}
The nominal weights method for a single anchor test assumes that, after accounting for the number of items on the total and anchor tests, mean performance on each test is equal in terms of proportion correct. This assumption is simply extended here to multiple anchors, where mean performance in terms of proportion correct is assumed to be equal for each individual across all anchors and the total test.

Postmultiplying $\Bmu_{x_P}$ by a row vector of 1s with length $m$, denoted by $\Bone^{\prime}$, produces an $n \times m$ matrix where each column contains the mean proportion correct for each individual on $X$. Under the assumption of equivalent mean proportion correct, $\Bmu_{x_P}\Bone^{\prime} = \Bmu_{v_P}$, which leads to
\begin{align}
  \Bgamma_X\Bone^{\prime} &= (\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V)^{-1}\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{x_P}\Bone^{\prime}K_X \nonumber \\
  &= (\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V)^{-1}\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}K_X. \label{eqn:reg4}
\end{align}
Postmultiplying by $\BK_V\BK_V^{-1}$ then reduces Equation~\eqref{eqn:reg4} to
\begin{align}
  \Bgamma_X\Bone^{\prime} &= (\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V)^{-1}\BK_V^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}^{\prime}\Bmu_{v_P}\BK_V\BK_V^{-1}K_X \nonumber \\
  &= \BK_V^{-1}K_X, \label{eqn:reg5}
\end{align}
which can be simplified further by postmultiplying by a column vector of length $m$ containing only $\frac{1}{m}$, i.e., $\Bone\frac{1}{m}$, as
\begin{align}
  \Bgamma_X\Bone^{\prime}\Bone\frac{1}{m} &= \BK_V^{-1}\Bone\frac{K_X}{m} \nonumber \\
  \Bgamma_X &= \begin{bmatrix}
  K_X/(K_{V_1}m) \\
  K_X/(K_{V_2}m) \\
  \vdots \\
  K_X/(K_{V_m}m)
  \end{bmatrix}. \label{eqn:multinominalb}
\end{align}
Equation~\eqref{eqn:multinominalb}, and the equivalent for $Y$, provide the nominal weights $\gamma$ terms needed to estimate the unobserved means in \eqref{eqn:mxq2} and \eqref{eqn:myp}.

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Frequency estimation

\subsection{Frequency estimation}
\label{sec:appendFreq}
When using frequency estimation with multiple anchors, the multivariate score distribution of $X$ and $V_1, V_2, \dots, V_m$ for the synthetic population is obtained as
\begin{equation}
\Pr(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) = w_P\Pr_P(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) + w_Q\Pr_Q(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m), \label{eqn:synthdistx2}
\end{equation}
and the distribution of $Y$ and $\BV$ is obtained similarly as
\begin{equation}
\Pr(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) = w_P\Pr_P(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) + w_Q\Pr_Q(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m). \label{eqn:synthdisty2}
\end{equation}
Like in the single anchor case, the distributions $\Pr_Q(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)$ and $\Pr_Q(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)$ are unavailable, and must be estimated indirectly. This estimation is made possible by assuming that the conditional distributions of $X$ given the anchors and $Y$ given the anchors are population invariant. This results in
\begin{equation}
\Pr_Q(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) = \frac{\Pr_P(x, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)}{\Pr_P(v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)}\Pr_Q(v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m), \label{eqn:xq}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
\Pr_P(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m) = \frac{\Pr_Q(y, v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)}{\Pr_Q(v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m)}\Pr_P(v_1, v_2, \dots, v_m), \label{eqn:yp}
\end{equation}
which are used in Equations~\eqref{eqn:synthdistx2} and \eqref{eqn:synthdisty2} to obtain the multivariate synthetic distributions. Note that Equations~\eqref{eqn:xq} and \eqref{eqn:yp} are simple generalizations of equations for equating with one anchor \citep[e.g.,][]{kolen2014test, vondavier2004kernel} and equating with two \citep{moses2010use} and three anchors \citep{angoff1984scales}.

