\section{Error in equating}
\label{sec:appendError}
In simulation and resampling studies, equating functions are typically compared based on both random and systematic error (or ``differences''), where the first is estimated by the standard error of equating $SE$ and the second by the $bias$. In the \pkg{equate} package, error is estimated in terms of the criterion equating function $link_Y(x)$ and estimate $\widehat{link}_{Yr}(x)$ for samples $r = 1, 2, \dots, R$. Systematic error is estimated as
\begin{equation}
  bias = \widehat{\overline{link}}_{Y}(x) - link_Y(x),
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
  \widehat{\overline{link}}_{Y}(x) = \frac{1}{R}\sum_{r=1}^{R}\widehat{link}_{Yr}(x)
\end{equation}
is the average estimated equated score over $R$ samples. The random error is estimated as
\begin{equation}
  SE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{R}\sum_{r=1}^{R}[\widehat{link}_{Yr}(x) - \widehat{\overline{link}}_Y(x)]^2}.
\end{equation}
Combining both systematic error and random error, the root mean squared error is estimated as
\begin{equation}
  RMSE = \sqrt{bias^2 + SE^2}.
\end{equation}

